{{Infobox journal | title = Journal of Law and Religion | cover = | editor = [[Center for the Study of Law and Religion]] | discipline = [[Law and religion]] | former_names = | abbreviation = J. Law Religion | bluebook = J.L. & Relig. | publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]] | country = United States | frequency = Annual | history = 1982-present | openaccess = | license = | impact = | impact-year = | website = https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-law-and-religion | link1 = | link1-name = | link2 = | link2-name = | JSTOR = | OCLC = | LCCN = | CODEN = | ISSN = 0748-0814 | eISSN = 2163-3088 }}
The '''''Journal of Law and Religion''''' is a peer-reviewed, interdisciplinary journal published through [[Cambridge University Press]] and edited by the [[Center for the Study of Law and Religion]] at [[Emory University School of Law]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-law-and-religion|title=Journal of Law and Religion|last=|first=|date=|website=Cambridge Core|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=7 October 2017}}</ref> Its primary interests include topics related to the relationship between religion and law, including subjects related to theological [[jurisprudence]] and [[political theology]].<ref name=":0" />
The journal was founded at [[Hamline University School of Law]] by the Harvard Law professor [[Harold J. Berman]] in 1982 along with Stephen B.Young, then Dean of the law school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hamline.edu/HUNewsDetail.aspx?id=2110|title=Journal of Law & Religion Salutes 25 Years of "Building Community and Deepening Understanding"|last=|first=|date=|website=Hamline University Law School|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=7 October 2017}}</ref> The Council on Religion and Law and Harvard Divinity School Professor [[James Luther Adams]] were also instrumental in starting the Journal. The goal of the Journal was to provide multiple frameworks of analysis for the study and discussion of structures of positive law. The Journal moved to the Center for the Study of Law and Religion at [[Emory University School of Law|Emory]] in 2013, two years prior to Hamline's merger with [[William Mitchell College of Law]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nationaljurist.com/national-jurist-magazine/journal-law-and-religion-moves-hamline-emory|title=Journal of Law and Religion moves from Hamline to Emory|last=|first=|date=8 August 2013|website=The National Jurist|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=7 October 2017}}</ref>
The Journal's co-editors include Silas Allard, [[Abdullahi Ahmed An-Na'im]], [[Michael Broyde]], M. Christian Green, [[Michael J. Perry]], and [[John Witte, Jr.]]<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://cslr.law.emory.edu/scholarship/journal-law-religion.html|title=Journal of Law and Religion|last=|first=|date=|website=Emory University School of Law|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=7 October 2017}}</ref>
